The Night of Unsounded Bells: Kel'Shadra's processional bells fell silent by decree at the moment of institutional collapse.
A reform bloc had attempted to expose falsified absolutions and coerced reclassifications: sealed transfer books proved donors purchased legal innocence while debtors were routed below as disposable labor.
The Chamber of Redactions triggered emergency doctrinal authority: bell silence decree, warden inversion protocol reassigning Reliquary units to internal suppression, contested ledgers shattered into memory shards.
The shattered gate at Kel'Shadra's upper approach was broken by internal actors attempting escape with unaltered records; the records did not leave.
Synchronization collapse cascaded across Kel'Shadra's layers: emergency controls became instruments of deeper harm.
Cipher-tradition practitioners operated on both sides — the reform faction using archive-access techniques to expose falsified absolutions; the Chamber using equivalent manipulation to suppress evidence.
Cleric-tradition practitioners developed sustained miracle-channel techniques in the mass-casualty aftermath, predating the formal Priest schism by generations.
Matriarchal authority consolidated in the Gloamvault; upper order changed iconography; lower order kept the machinery running.
Coercive memory governance was professionalized rather than ended: the Night did not destroy the system, it restructured it.
The event's name refers to the silence as a message: the bells that rang to announce each absolution rang nothing — because the absolution system had been suspended.
The Night did not produce institutional death; it produced institutional mutation under the cover of emergency authority.
The reform bloc's evidence was real; the records that would have confirmed it were destroyed; the institutional mechanism that could have forced disclosure did not exist.

